{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487121"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:58:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:58:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"257"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"257","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/257"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.55,0.14,0.07,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"257"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90145"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"257","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/257"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"257"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74387"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3525"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5009"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5010"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30824"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42042"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90145"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 45-year-old man goes to see his general practitioner after an episode of epigastric pain which lasted four hours and then resolved spontaneously. There is nothing else to be gleaned from the history and the physical examination is unremarkable.\u00a0A CT scan is performed and this is normal apart from an enhancing, homogenous 5cm mass in the region of the left adrenal gland. The margins are well defined and the lesion appears to be encapsulated.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Repeat CT in six months","Urinary and serum hormone levels","CT-guided needle biopsy","Reassurance and no follow-up","MRI scan"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe scenario presented here describes an \u2018adrenal incidentaloma.\u2019 In otherwords, an adrenal lesion which is identified on imaging studies performed for other reasons, in the absence of directly suspected adrenal-related symptoms. The size of this lesion may indicate that intervention is necessary depending on further information. This is an adrenal adenoma and on size alone, needs to be removed to exclude malignancy. Any tumour greater than 4cm should be considered for excision.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA first step is to determine whether the lesion is functional or not. Hence, \u003Cstrong\u003Eurinary and serum hormone levels\u003C/strong\u003E is most appropriate at this stage, considering the possible diagnoses of Conn\u0027s, Cushing\u0027s or phaeochromocytoma. Based on these results, if biopsy or surgery is indicated then further work-up may involve \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI\u003C/strong\u003E to delineate soft tissue anatomy, or an \u003Cstrong\u003Eimage-guided biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E. It is crucial to know if the tumour is hormonally active before biopsy or surgery since certain adrenal lesions (e.g. pheochromocytoma) has very significant perioperative and intraoperative considerations for the surgeon and anaesthetist. \u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance\u003C/strong\u003E alone is not appropriate, nor is a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT follow-up in 6 months\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Adrenal lesions are relatively common incidental findings on cross sectional radiology."],"references":["Ye L-i, Yuan X-x, Chen M-k, et al. Management of adrenal incidentaloma: the role of adrenalectomy may be underestimated. BMC Surgery 2016; 16:41-47.","Gendy R, Rashid P. Incidental adrenal masses - A primary care approach Aust Fam Physician. 2017; 46:385-90."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74387"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"257"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74387"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-12T16:11:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-12T16:16:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"257"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90145"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags